Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm wide wedges
(no need to peel!). Pop the wedges on a large #baking tray{} in a single layer.
Drizzle with @oil{}, sprinkle over half the @Peri Peri seasoning{1} then season
with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, then spread out and roast on the top
shelf of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

> Use two baking trays if necessary, you want the potatoes nicely spread out.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pop the
@British chicken thighs{4} into a #bowl{} with the garlic, remaining peri peri
seasoning, half the @cider vinegar{15%ml}, a drizzle of @oil{} and season with
plenty of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Mix well to coat then set aside for
~{5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g} then pop them into a #small bowl{} with
the remaining @cider vinegar{15%ml}, a drizzle of @olive oil{}, a pinch of
@sugar{pinch} (if you have some) and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Mix
together then set aside.

Heat a #frying pan{} over medium high heat (no oil!). Once hot, place the thighs
flat in the pan and cook until golden brown all over, ~{3-4%minutes} each
side. Lower the heat to medium and continue to cook until cooked through, a
further ~{6-8%minutes}. Turn occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile in a small bowl, mix together the @mayonnaise{64%g} and
@sriracha sauce{15%g} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cut the
@glazed burger buns{2} in half (like a sandwich) then pop in the oven for
the last ~{2-3%minutes} of the potato cooking time, until warmed through.

Pop the burger buns on #plates{} and divide half the mayonnaise mixture between
the bottom of the buns. Top with the chicken and the top of the burger bun.
Serve with the wedges, tomato salad and the remaining mayonnaise on the side.
Enjoy!